{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"Integrate the task-decomposition SOTA research (docs/research/task-decomposition-sota-2026.md, commit 143d5074e, ticket englacial-communal-conure/d39b) into the plan-review gate: validate each recommendation experimentally with evals FIRST, implement only behind its results gate, then dogfood in production review. Per operator direction (2026-07-15): no A/B testing - validation is eval-based (the E-gates below), post-ship observation is dogfooding via R7 instrumentation, and the approach must be clearly documented at every step.\n\n## Context\nGATE TERMS: each child R1-R7 story carries its own falsifiable pass/fail thresholds (drawn from the report's section-6 experiment table) INSIDE its Acceptance Criteria - the child ACs are the authoritative 'gate rows'; this epic does not duplicate the numbers. R6 is the one deliberate exception: a deterministic pass-4 coaching move with no detection behavior ships first with no eval gate (validated by dogfooding via R7 metrics). Experiment ids follow the report's numbering; E4 (the in-situ A/B experiment) is deliberately DROPPED per the operator's no-A/B directive, which is why the experiment set is E1/E2/E3/E5/E6. INCONCLUSIVE-GATE RULE: an experiment that fails its own validity gate (e.g. E1 kappa < 0.7) or returns an ambiguous result gets at most ONE documented re-run with changed method; if still not clearly passing, every dependent R-story closes deferred with the results recorded - ambiguity never rounds up to a pass. ORDERING: first wave after E1 is R7 + R6 (instrumentation and the no-gate move), so dogfood monitoring exists before any detection change lands; R2/R3/R4 each touch criteria_routing.json and land serially in any order (file-impact keeps them out of one batch); R1 does not depend on R5 (the probe is effective without the kernel sub-answer; R5 strengthens its verification later); R5's IMPACT_MODEL_VERSION bump is coordinated at claim time with the floor-split story's own potential bump so the corpus segments cleanly (one bump train, never two half-bumps).\nThe report's §5 mined this store's own history: post-claim description edits on 16/505 claimed work tickets (3.2%), 15 substantive; of 8 with persisted reviews, 3 were review MISSES sharing one defect class (plan asserts a capability an existing module lacks: dc58, db7b, 5886) and 4 were advisories applied only post-claim (latency, not blindness). Small n: 3/8 identifies the defect CLASS (binomial 95% CI 9-76%), it is not a precise miss rate - child E1 re-verifies these claims before anything depends on them. §6 defines R1-R7, each with a falsifiable experiment. Implementation targets: src/rebar/llm/plan_review/ (orchestrator, det_floor.py, passes.py, criteria_routing.json), src/rebar/llm/review_kernel/ (SHARED with code-review - R5 requires the E5 non-regression gate), src/rebar/llm/reviewers/plan_review_*.md. Calibration assets in docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/ are extended, not replaced. This epic runs alongside the calibration-3 line (task relishable-ammonitic-hoverfly, story large-sleepful-needlefish); implementation children that touch criteria_routing.json/review_kernel sequence after the floor-split story to avoid file conflicts.\n\n## Success Criteria\n- Every implemented recommendation has a committed docs/experiments/ writeup showing its gate row passed before implementation; every rejected/deferred recommendation has the failing result recorded.\n- The gate ships with no blocking-FP regression: validated changes are incorporated DIRECTLY into the packaged review process (no config-flag or overlay gating - operator direction 2026-07-15); new criteria enter at advisory POSTURE first where their child's gate terms say so, with R7 dogfood monitoring: when a criterion's trailing blocking-FP proxy exceeds 10% (the **blocking-FP proxy** for a criterion is the fraction of that criterion's BLOCKING findings, over a trailing window of reviews, that are subsequently adjudicated false-positive / not-block-worthy — measured by R7's instrumentation against E1's committed finding-adjudication ground-truth corpus; 10% is the demotion threshold), its registry posture is demoted to advisory by an ordinary criteria_routing.json change (precedent: calibration 3 demoted T5e to advisory on FP evidence, task relishable-ammonitic-hoverfly; T3/T10 are the precedent for keeping routinely-ignored criteria non-blocking in the first place).\n- The plan-review methodology remains documented: docs/plan-review-gate.md reflects every landed change.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] E1 ground-truth corpora are frozen and committed under docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/ with a versioned README (outcome corpus + finding-adjudication corpus, inter-rater kappa >= 0.7 recorded).\n- [ ] Each experiment child (E1, E2, E3, E5, E6 - no E4, see Context) is closed with its results committed as a docs/experiments/ writeup (the repo artifact is the criterion; ticket comments mirror it).\n- [ ] Each recommendation child (R1-R7) is either landed through Gerrit with its own AC gate terms demonstrably passed (R6's terms are ship-first: deterministic rendering + validator compliance), or closed/deferred with the failing result recorded - no detection-bearing recommendation implemented without its eval gate.\n- [ ] All landed criteria/rubric changes are incorporated directly into the packaged registry/rubrics (no config-flag or overlay gating), with R7 dogfood monitoring documented, and docs/plan-review-gate.md updated to match."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784162332013955001,"uuid":"350e4c67-5003-4b55-8634-d2b83714a77d"}